\begin{frame}
\begin{block}{What is R Markdown and R Notebook}
\protect\hypertarget{what-is-r-markdown-and-r-notebook}{}
R Markdown provides an authoring framework for data science. You can use
a single R Markdown file to both

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  save and execute code
\item
  generate high quality reports that can be shared with an audience
\end{itemize}

R Notebooks are an implementation of Literate Programming that allows
for direct interaction with R while producing a reproducible document
with publication-quality output.

An \textbf{R Notebook} is an R Markdown document \emph{with chunks that
can be executed independently and interactively, with output visible
immediately beneath the input}.

(Reference: \href{https://bookdown.org/yihui/rmarkdown/notebook.html}{R
Markdown: The Definitive Guide, 3.2 Notebook})
\end{block}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\begin{block}{Two Goodies}
\protect\hypertarget{two-goodies}{}
\begin{itemize}
\item
  \textbf{Important}: Implementation of Reproducible Research and
  Literate Programming
\item
  \textbf{Useful} to Render into Various Formats: R Notebook (HTML), R
  Markdown (HTML), PDF, MS Word, MS Powerpoint, Ioslides Presentation
  (HTML), Slidy Presentation (HTML), Beamer Presentation (PDF), etc.
\end{itemize}
\end{block}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\begin{block}{Reproducible Research and Literate Programming}
\protect\hypertarget{reproducible-research-and-literate-programming}{}
\begin{block}{Literate Programming by D. Knuth}
\protect\hypertarget{literate-programming-by-d.-knuth}{}
Literate programming is an approach to programming introduced by Donald
Knuth in which a program is given as an explanation of the program logic
in a natural language, such as English, interspersed with snippets of
macros and traditional source code, from which a compilable source code
can be generated
\end{block}

\begin{block}{\href{https://www.brainyquote.com/quotes/donald_knuth_181634}{D.
Knuth}}
\protect\hypertarget{d.-knuth}{}
Let us change our traditional attitude to the construction of programs:
Instead of imagining that our main task is to instruct a computer what
to do, let us concentrate rather on explaining to human beings what we
want a computer to do.
\end{block}
\end{block}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\begin{block}{Reproducible Research - Quote from a
\href{https://www.coursera.org/learn/reproducible-research}{Coursera
Course}}
\protect\hypertarget{reproducible-research---quote-from-a-coursera-course}{}
Reproducible research is the idea that data analyses, and more
generally, scientific claims, are published with their data and software
code so that others may verify the findings and build upon them. The
need for reproducibility is increasing dramatically as data analyses
become more complex, involving larger datasets and more sophisticated
computations. Reproducibility allows for people to focus on the actual
content of a data analysis, rather than on superficial details reported
in a written summary. In addition, reproducibility makes an analysis
more useful to others because the data and code that actually conducted
the analysis are available.
\end{block}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\begin{block}{R Markdown workflow,
\href{https://r4ds.had.co.nz/r-markdown-workflow.html\#r-markdown-workflow}{R
for Data Science}}
\protect\hypertarget{r-markdown-workflow-r-for-data-science}{}
R Markdown is also important because it so tightly integrates prose and
code. This makes it a great analysis notebook because it lets you
develop code and record your thoughts. It:

\begin{itemize}
\item
  Records what you did and why you did it. Regardless of how great your
  memory is, if you don't record what you do, there will come a time
  when you have forgotten important details. Write them down so you
  don't forget!
\item
  Supports rigorous thinking. You are more likely to come up with a
  strong analysis if you record your thoughts as you go, and continue to
  reflect on them. This also saves you time when you eventually write up
  your analysis to share with others.
\item
  Helps others understand your work. It is rare to do data analysis by
  yourself, and you'll often be working as part of a team. A lab
  notebook helps you share why you did it with your colleagues or lab
  mates.
\end{itemize}
\end{block}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\begin{block}{Code Chunk}
\protect\hypertarget{code-chunk}{}
\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  When you execute or run a code within the notebook, the results appear
  beneath the code.
\item
  Try executing this chunk by clicking the Run button, a triangle
  pointing right, within the chunk or by placing your cursor inside it
  and pressing Ctrl+Shift+Enter (Win) or Cmd+Shift+Enter (Mac).
\item
  Add a new chunk by clicking the Insert Chunk button on the toolbar or
  by pressing Ctrl+Option+I (Win) or Cmd+Option+I (Mac).
\item
  When you save the notebook, an HTML file containing the code and
  output will be saved alongside it (click the Preview button or press
  Ctrl+Shift+K (Win) or Cmd+Shift+K (Mac) to preview the HTML file).
\item
  The preview shows you a rendered HTML copy of the contents of the
  editor. Consequently, unlike Knit, \emph{Preview does not run any R
  code chunks. Instead, the output of the chunk when it was last run in
  the editor is displayed}.
\end{itemize}
\end{block}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}[fragile]
\begin{block}{Markdown Language -- or use WYSIWYG editor}
\protect\hypertarget{markdown-language-or-use-wysiwyg-editor}{}
\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Headers: \#, \#\#, \#\#\#, \#\#\#\#
\item
  Lists: 1. 2. \ldots, *
\item
  Links: \href{http://example.com}{linked phrase}
\item
  Images: \texttt{!{[}alt\ text{]}(figures/filename.jpg)}
\item
  Block quotes'' \textgreater{} (block)
\item
  \LaTeX~ equations: e.g.~\texttt{\$\textbackslash{}frac\{a\}\{b\}\$}
  for \(\frac{a}{b}\)
\item
  Horizontal rules: Three or more asterisks or dashes (*** or - - - )
\item
  Tables
\item
  Footnotes
\item
  Bibliographies and Citations
\item
  Slide breaks
\item
  \emph{Italicized text} by \texttt{\_italic\_}, \textbf{Bold text} by
  \texttt{**bold**}
\item
  Superscripts, Subscripts, Strikethrough text
\end{itemize}
\end{block}

\begin{frame}[fragile]{Data Transforamtion with \texttt{dplyr}}
\protect\hypertarget{data-transforamtion-with-dplyr}{}
\begin{block}{\texttt{dplyr}
\href{https://dplyr.tidyverse.org}{Overview}}
\protect\hypertarget{dplyr-overview}{}
dplyr is a grammar of data manipulation, providing a consistent set of
verbs that help you solve the most common data manipulation challenges:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \texttt{select()} picks variables based on their names.
\item
  \texttt{filter()} picks cases based on their values.
\item
  \texttt{mutate()} adds new variables that are functions of existing
  variables
\item
  \texttt{summarise()} reduces multiple values down to a single summary.
\item
  \texttt{arrange()} changes the ordering of the rows.
\item
  \texttt{group\_by()} takes an existing tbl and converts it into a
  grouped tbl.
\end{itemize}

You can learn more about them in vignette(``dplyr''). As well as these
single-table verbs, dplyr also provides a variety of two-table verbs,
which you can learn about in vignette(``two-table'').

If you are new to dplyr, the best place to start is
\href{http://r4ds.had.co.nz/transform.html}{the data transformation
chapter in R for data science}.
\end{block}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}[fragile]
\begin{block}{\href{https://dplyr.tidyverse.org/reference/arrange.html}{\texttt{arrange}}
and \texttt{Pipe\ \%\textgreater{}\%}}
\protect\hypertarget{arrange-and-pipe}{}
\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \texttt{arrange()} orders the rows of a data frame by the values of
  selected columns.
\end{itemize}

Unlike other \texttt{dplyr} verbs, \texttt{arrange()} largely ignores
grouping; you need to explicitly mention grouping variables (`or use
.by\_group = TRUE) in order to group by them, and functions of variables
are evaluated once per data frame, not once per group.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \href{https://r4ds.had.co.nz/pipes.html}{\texttt{pipes}} in R for Data
  Science.
\end{itemize}
\end{block}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}[fragile]
\begin{block}{\href{https://dplyr.tidyverse.org/reference/summarise.html}{\texttt{summarise}
or \texttt{summarize}}}
\protect\hypertarget{summarise-or-summarize}{}
\begin{block}{Summary functions}
\protect\hypertarget{summary-functions}{}
So far our summarise() examples have relied on sum(), max(), and mean().
But you can use any function in summarise() so long as it meets one
criteria: the function must take a vector of values as input and return
a single value as output. Functions that do this are known as summary
functions and they are common in the field of descriptive statistics.
Some of the most useful summary functions include:

\begin{enumerate}
\tightlist
\item
  Measures of location - mean(x), median(x), quantile(x, 0.25), min(x),
  and max(x)
\item
  Measures of spread - sd(x), var(x), IQR(x), and mad(x)
\item
  Measures of position - first(x), nth(x, 2), and last(x)
\item
  Counts - n\_distinct(x) and n(), which takes no arguments, and returns
  the size of the current group or data frame.
\item
  Counts and proportions of logical values - sum(!is.na(x)), which
  counts the number of TRUEs returned by a logical test; mean(y == 0),
  which returns the proportion of TRUEs returned by a logical test.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  if\_else(), recode(), case\_when()
\end{itemize}
\end{block}
\end{block}
\end{frame}

\protect\hypertarget{ggplot2-overview}{}
\texttt{ggplot2} is a system for declaratively creating graphics, based
on \href{https://amzn.to/2ef1eWp}{The Grammar of Graphics}. You provide
the data, tell ggplot2 how to map variables to aesthetics, what
graphical primitives to use, and it takes care of the details.

\textbf{Examples}

\begin{verbatim}
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))
\end{verbatim}

\begin{verbatim}
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = class, y = hwy))
\end{verbatim}

\textbf{Template}

\begin{verbatim}
ggplot(data = <DATA>) + 
  <GEOM_FUNCTION>(mapping = aes(<MAPPINGS>))
\end{verbatim}
\end{block}
\end{block}
\end{frame}

    \begin{itemize}
    \tightlist
    \item
      country: factor with 142 levels
    \item
      continent: factor with 5 levels
    \item
      year: ranges from 1952 to 2007 in increments of 5 years
    \item
      lifeExp: life expectancy at birth, in years
    \item
      pop: population
    \item
      gdpPercap: GDP per capita (US\$, inflation-adjusted)
    \end{itemize}
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
